===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|countable}} An [[outer]] [[garment]] [[cover]]ing the upper [[torso]] and [[arms]].<sup>{{w|Coat (clothing)|Wp}}</sup>
#* {{RQ:Weyman Chippinge Borough|I|01|passage=It was April 22, 1831, and a young man was walking down Whitehall in the direction of Parliament Street. He wore shepherd's plaid trousers and the swallow-tail '''coat''' of the day, with a figured muslin cravat wound about his wide-spread collar.}}
#* {{RQ:Christie Autobiography|II|4|passage=Mind you, clothes were clothes in those days.{{...}}Frills, ruffles, flounces, lace, complicated seams and gores: not only did they sweep the ground and have to be held up in one hand elegantly as you walked along, but they had little capes or '''coats''' or feather boas.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A [[covering]] of [[material]], such as [[paint]].<sup>{{w|Paint|Wp}}</sup>
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=5|passage=Fruit of all kinds, in '''coat''' / Rough or smooth rined, or bearded [[husk]], or [[shell]].}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} The [[fur]] or [[feathers]] covering an animal's [[skin]].<sup>{{w|Coat (animal)|Wp}}</sup>
#: {{ux|en|When the dog shed its '''coat''', it left hair all over the furniture and the carpet.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable|nautical}} [[canvas|Canvas]] [[painted]] with [[thick]] [[tar]] and secured round a [[mast]] or [[bowsprit]] to prevent [[water]] running [[down]] the sides into the [[hold]] (now made of [[rubber]] or [[leather]]).
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[petticoat]].
#* {{RQ:Locke Education|148}}
#*: a child in '''coats'''
# The [[habit]] or [[vesture]] of an order of men, indicating the order or office; [[cloth]].
#* {{RQ:Swift The Grand Question Debated of Hamilton's Bawn}}
#*: Men of his '''coat''' should be minding their prayers.
#* '''1609''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''A Lover's Compaint''
#*: She was sought by spirits of richest '''coat'''.
# A [[coat of arms]].<sup>{{w|Coat of arms|Wp}}</sup>
#*{{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-1|I|v|passage=[[Hark]], countrymen! either renew the fight, / Or tear the lions out of England's '''coat'''.}}
# A [[coat card]].
#* {{RQ:Massinger The Old Law}}
#*: Here's a trick of discarded cards of us! We were ranked with '''coats''' as long as old master lived.

